<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Gorgash,<P>Some good thoughts on the reproduceable dungeon idea - thanks... here are some responses:<P>On not being able to wander the dungeon to get to know it... well, yes, certainly a possible disadvantage, but... If the idea is to get to more of a pencil and paper feel to dungeons, then you don't know anything about a dungeon when you go there. That was a great part of D&D. However, we must also remember that we have Muse to rely on, so I'm sure we will at least have maps in hand when we enter the dungeon.<P>On deaths in the group... First, this depends on which idea is developed - strictly one-group-at-a-time zones vs. Reproduceable zones. If it's reproduceable zones, the dead player could return as long as his group is still in there.<P><BR>If it's the other... well, I love this part. I think it's great that a group might not be able to successfully complete the dungeon if they have too many deaths. OK, EQ is not permanent death, nor should it be! It's great that our characters can be fearless, ok a little fear of Exp loss. But here is a part of the game that will at least simulate the feeling of really trying to accomplish something without dying. Sure, you may have to wait a day or a few hours to try again if you fail, but imagine the satisfaction of finally completing the whole dungeon with minimal loss!<P>In general, these styles of dungeons are not meant to meet anyone's entire EQ experience needs and perhaps no major no drop items should be placed here. The idea is to provide a pencil and paper feel dungeon that groups must try to complete on their own with no distractions. Other dungeon types should still exist in the game.<P>Well, this is a fun discussion... keep it up!<BR><P>------------------<BR>Rylius Elfheart<BR>Paladin of Tunare, 25th Season<BR>Dragonhood of Marr<BR>Mith Marr Server
