<HR size="1" color="#a62a2a">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Muse:<P>Let me see if I can paraphrase <I>your</I> logic:<P>It's not possible to 'do' most dungeons in the game today for two reasons.  First, because the range of levels from top to bottom is too high in most dungeons.  Second, because most of the interesting encounters are camped, so you either have to pass up all the interesting stuff, or join the camp.<P>To answer the first point, I have to go back to my D&D days (which are longer ago than I care to admit).  When we 'did' a dungeon in D&D, we would go in and fight our way down until we had more loot than we could carry, or (more likely) until we met something that kicked our butts. Then we'd limp back to town to sell stuff and rest.  When we had recovered, we'd go back in, and hopefully make it farther the next time.  When we were finally able to defeat the biggest nasties in the place, we'd usually leave and never look back.<P>I don't see why Everquest dungeons can't work the same way.  There's no reason (except for the few one-way doors) that you have to be able to fight the whole dungeon in one sitting, or even one level.  <P>To answer the second point, we have to go back to my original post.  How do we stop people from camping?  Either we nerf camping or we make not camping more rewarding.<P>The problem is, anything you do to make not-camping more rewarding will make camping more rewarding still. If the dungeon is set up as an increasingly difficult challenge, for each group there's always going to be a "sweet spot", where the level of challenge best matches their abilities. Unless you somehow limit the ability to profit from staying in that spot (read: nerf camping), it's always going to be advantageous to stay there.<P>Finally, I'm afraid I have to agree with you that Verant seems to have pretty much accepted that not everyone who plays will get to do everything in the game.  That bugs me too, especially since I'm one of the people who will probably never get to do a lot of it.  But, in Verant's defense (since I'm being their apologist), that's intentional too.  Verant would prefer that <B>nobody</B> were able to do everything in the game.  The only reason some people have is that their capacity for obsessive game playing exceeds Verant's ability to create new challenges.  Is that the best way to design a game so that people have fun?  I don't know, but it may be the only way to get the obsessive powergamers into the same world with the rest of us and still have a chance.
</FONT>
