 <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Muse wrote:<BR><B>This game, though, caters to the extreme one end of the spectrum where you must devote your life to hitting 50th in order to see some of the coolest parts of the world. I think everyone who buys the game should be able to do that, and the way it is now we can't, and Verant is okay with that, and that's what bugs me.</B><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>I am in full agreement with Muse here.  Everyone who buys the game should have the same rights to see everything the game has to offer.  My main character is 22nd level, with a /played of about 12 days.  I shudder to think of what that time will be should I ever make 30th.  I have given up any hope of ever seeing 40th level.  Why should I miss out on the things a 40th level character can do just because I have other interests outside of EQ?  I pay the same amount for my 6-10 hours a week on EQ as do the folks who put in 60 hours a week.  Twisting this around a little bit, aren't I actually a more valuable customer to Verant, because for the same amount of money I use far less of their resources?  <P>Basically, though, Verant runs EQ just like MUD admins run their games - those who sink all the time into get all the rewards.  That works for MUDs though, because by and large they're FREE.  It doesn't fly when all your customers are being paid the same amount, but some are being denied parts of the game because they don't have the time to put into it that others do.<P>OK, that's long enough for now.  I still enjoy EQ, but only so long as my friends are around to group with.  With every hour of playtime I lose to a sudden death incurred through no action of my own (Grimfeather, anyone?), the fun:work ratio of EQ drops another notch.  If it drops much more, I'll expect them to be paying me for the experience  <IMG SRC="http://www.eqatlas.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P><P>------------------<BR><B>Arilan</B><BR>22 Cleric of Rodcet Nife<BR>Bertox server
