<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Something someone said triggered this thought.  I was thinking how they want us to do stuff the preferred way.  But every time I do do that, I wind up getting killed the first couple of times.  Verant has responded to this issue by stating that every area has a learning curve, and is therefore more dangerous until you learn it, and therefore you are simply experiencing what they expect.<P>I believe in that concept in theory, however I don't think that in practice in EQ it is a really valid excuse for why I have to die in a new area.  A valid reason for dying in a new area is that I didn't realize that these monsters had lots of healers, or that there is a pit trap in the hallway, or that all the monsters are resistant to my spells.  The reasons in EQ that I die are more often things like pathing bugs, popping monsters, monsters aggroing from nearby rooms that I didn't know about, etc.  Yes, there is a learning curve, but it's a learning curve that has nothing to do with my character and monsters, but instead with game issues that have always existed.  In my opinion, balancing a game with bugs isn't "balancing."<P>------------------<BR>Muse<BR>Bard and Cartographer
</FONT>
